Background of the Data

Francis Galton, a cousin of Charles Darwin, studied the relationship between parent heights and the heights of their offspring. His pioneering 1886 article is the first appearance of regression analysis in print. He originated many statistical terms and concepts, including regression, correlation, deviate, quartile, and percentile, plus median for the midpoint of a distribution. The galtonheightdata dataset was created under the direction of Dr.James A. Hanley using Galtons original paper notebooks containing the measurement data. You can access the galtonfamiliesmain.csv and galtonfamiliessub.csv datasets from their description page, which also contains variable definitions.

Create Analysis Datasets

Dataset #1

Load the galtonfamiliesmain.csv and galtonfamiliessub.csv datasets above under the Setup header and use glimpse() to explore their structures. Use your code from Project 1 and/or draw from the Project 1 solutions to assemble a dataset below that meets the following criteria. Use datatable() from the DT package to display the result.

  • contains these variables:
    • familyid = ID number of the family, with 136A recoded as 205
    • num_children= the number of children in the family
    • father_ht = the height of the father
    • mother_ht = the transmuted (per Galton) height of the mother
    • midparent = the average of the parents heights
    • child_sex= whether the child is a son or a daughter, all lower case
    • child_ht = the height of the child with daughter heights transmuted
  • is arranged according to:
    • ascending order of familyid
    • sons before daughters within family
    • in order of height within each sex of child
data <- data_sub %>%
  mutate(
    Father = FatherR + 60,
    Mother = MotherR + 60,
    Height = HeightR + 60,
    FamilyID = as.character(FamilyID)) %>%
  bind_rows(data_main) %>%
   transmute(familyid = as.numeric(ifelse(FamilyID == "136A", 205, FamilyID)),
             num_children = Children,
             father_ht = Father,
             mother_ht = (Mother *1.08),
             midparent = (Father + mother_ht)/2,
             child_sex = tolower(Child),
             child_ht = ifelse(Child == "Daughter", Height * 1.08, Height )) %>%
   arrange(familyid, desc(child_sex), desc(child_ht))

datatable(data)

Dataset #2

Select the variables familyid and num_children and reduce the dataset so that it contains only one row per family. Again, use datatable() from the DT package to display the result.

data2 <- data %>%
   group_by(familyid) %>%
   summarize(
      num_children = mean(num_children)
   )

datatable(data2)

Part 1: Parent/Child Heights

Galtons Visualization

In his original paper (linked above), Galton created several tables and diagrams. His Diagram Based on Table 1 of them is similar in concept to a scatterplot. Rather than dots, he grouped/tabulated the data, and then used the count of how many people were grouped at the coordinate pairs in his grid, with child as the x-axis and mid-parent as the y-axis. There are two scales: inches and deviations from 68.25 inches.

Updated Scatterplot #1

Create a scatterplot of child height (x-axis) versus mid-parent height (y-axis). Ordinarily, we might reverse the axes here because analysts would be more likely to model child height as a function of parent height, but we want to be able to compare the updated plot to Galtons original. Make your dots larger than the default and adjust transparency (alpha) to correct for overplotting and help show the density of points.

Also include the following.

  • use color in the aes to differentiate sons versus daughters
  • use scale_color_manual() to choose two informative colors
  • scale both axes so that there is a tick mark at every whole inch
  • use coord_fixed() so that the axes have the same unit spacing
  • add better x- and y-axis labels, including the units of measure
  • add an informative title (you may optionally include a subtitle)
  • add color = to labs() to set the legend title to "gender of child"
  • use theme_linedraw() to add some additional plot formatting
  • use theme() to move the legend to the bottom of the scatterplot
plot <- ggplot(data, aes(child_ht, midparent, color = child_sex)) + 
   geom_point(alpha = 0.2, size = 3.5) + 
   scale_color_manual(values = c("#E69F00", "#56B4E9")) +
   scale_x_continuous(n.breaks = 20) +
   scale_y_continuous(n.breaks = 15) +
   coord_fixed() +
   labs(color = "gender of child", title = "Comparing Average Heights of Parents to Their Children", subtitle = "Female Heights are Multiplied by 1.08") +
   xlab("Height of Child in Inches") + ylab("Midparents- Average of Parents' Heights in Inches")+
   theme_linedraw() +
   theme(legend.position = "bottom", axis.ticks.x = element_line(), axis.ticks.y = element_line())
plot

Updated Scatterplot #2

Remove the color coding for sons versus daughters from your plot, as well as any other coding related to it. Instead, choose n single color for the points and adjust both size and transparency (alpha) as needed to correct for overplotting and help show the density of points. Reset the aes so child height is the y variable and midparent height is the x variable. Add a fitted straight line to the plot. Update your labs accordingly.

plot2 <- ggplot(data, aes(midparent, child_ht)) + 
   geom_point(alpha = 0.4, size = 1, color = "#7570B3")  +
   scale_y_continuous(n.breaks = 20) +
   scale_x_continuous(n.breaks = 15) + 
   geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE, color = "#1B9E77") +
   coord_fixed() +
   labs(title = "Comparing Average Heights of Parents to Their Children", subtitle = "Female Heights are Multiplied by 1.08") +
   ylab("Height of Child in Inches") + xlab("Midparents- Average of Parents' Heights in Inches")+
   theme_linedraw() +
   theme(legend.position = "bottom", axis.ticks.x = element_line(), axis.ticks.y = element_line())
plot2

Create a barplot to show the distribution of the number of children per family. Set the bars to something other than the default width. Scale the x-axis so that there is a tick mark for each bar. Questions

Question 1: Do you think that your scatterplots are an improvement over Galtons original diagram? Are there any modifications and/or additions you would make to enhance the clarity or usefulness of your plots?

ANSWER

Yes, I think the scatterplots are an improvement over Galtons original diagram. Though the use of grouping the data based on location on the plot in the original data resulted in less overplotting, it was difficult to have a clear visualization of the data from this. The use of color-coding and increasing transparency within the new plots allowed for the information overall to be more clearly visible and readable for the typical person. Additional modifications that I would make to enhance the clarity of the plot would be to add the deviations in inches to the sides of the plot, as well as the horizontal and vertical lines through the origin that were in the original plot to mark where deviation is 0. I believe having these center lines helps to visualize which portion of the graph each point is in and their general relation between their x and y value.

Question 2: Explain the rationale behind the choices you made when creating your scatterplots and barplot, such as size, color, transparency, or other features. What motivated your decisions?

ANSWER

For the first scatterplot, The colors for the first plot are two colors easily distinguishable from one another for those that are color blind. This allows for it be be clear for all viewers which colors represent sons and which represent daughters. I also decided to have decently large dot sizes for this plot in order for each point to be more distinguishable from the next, especially in terms of being able to see whether a point is in fact a son or daughter. I also had very low transparency for this plot to try to offset the overplotting caused by having larger points. The combination of these created a graph that shows each individual point while also being able to see the locations of higher density on the plot.

For the second scatterplot, I decided to decrease the dot size in order to have less overlap in points, and allow each point to be more clearly visible. This felt more important now that color was no longer being used to distinguish between sons and daughters, so smaller points allows for them to be more separated. The points also now no longer need to be as distinguished between one another, as there is not a difference between each point (i.e.needing to see the color to determine if the child is a son or daughter). Thius means that we are now more focused on the general shape of the graph, which is more noticable when the points are smaller and contain less overlap. Having the midparents heights on the x-axis and childrens heights on the y-axis also resulted in the graph being produced smaller, so having smaller points then became even more necessary as the points were now shown closer together. Having smaller, non-color coded points and a smaller graph overall is also why I decided to use a higher alpha level, resulting in less trnasparency of the points. Now that each point was smaller, overplotting was less of an issue, so it mad more sense for each point to be more visible. Having a smaller graph and smaller points also resulted in points that are less compact with one another being harder to see, so decreasing the transparency of these points allowed them to stay visible. The colors chosen for the points and for the line of best fit are also colors that are within a color palette that is easily distinguishable for those that are color blind.

For the barplot, I decided to use the color #E69F00 because it is a color-blind friendly color. Even though the color is not being compared to another, I still thought it would be in best practice to use a color that is still color-blind friendly, and is easily distinguishable from the background. I also decided to have a bar for each number of children per family, which allows for the information to be most easily interpreted. I also have tick marks at every 20 units on the y-axis, which is a number that allows enough lines throughout the graph to be able to easily read the height of each bar, while also not being overly crowding and having too many number listed on the y-axis.

Question 3: Considering best practices, how does using coord_fixed() enhance the authenticity of the information shown in the scatterplots, such as the relationship and spread of the data?

ANSWER

coor_fixed increased the authenticity of the data by not overly showcasing the spread that occurred in mid-parents height. Without coord_fixed, it appeared as if the childrens heights were much more spread out and that the childrens heights varied much more than the mid-parents heights did. This also made it appear as though the general slope of the data was not as dramatic as it actually is, and that the parents heights had less of a relationship with the childrens heights than they actually do. We are now able to accurately interpret the differences between increase in midparent height compared to increases in childrens height by the physical change in distance, not only the number of squares.
